They are used, with vinegar, old wine, or honey wine, as the particular case requires, for the treatment of the mouth, teeth, ears, running sores, the genitals and chapS. To wounds they are applied on linen eloth, to sprains on wool. Used thus they are of great value, par- ticularly when old, as a medicament‚ curing fistula. They are injected for ulceration of the anus, genitals, and uterus, but applied as liniment for incipient gout and diseases of the joints. If moreover they are reboiled with omphacium to the consisteney of honey, they extract diseased teeth, and with a decoction of lupins and the plant chamaeleon are a wonderful healer of itch scab in beasts of burden. The crude lees are very beneficial as a fomentation for gout.

XXXVIII. Wild-olive leaves have the same qualities. Spodium from the young branches act as a powerful check on catarrhs, reduce inflam- mations of the eyes, cleanse sores that have eaten into the flesh and restore it, while they gently cauterize those that swell outhnds, dry them up and promote cicatrization. In other respects the proper-ties of wild and of cultivated olive are the same, except that the wild variety has this virtue of its own: a decoction of the leaves in honey is given in doses of three spoonfuls⁰ for spitting of blood.
